body:
Oh the issue is not with the $id
The problem is, the code generated has this line
`payload = make(models.B, 0, 50)` in get_all_responses.go

B is defined as
```go
// B b
// swagger:model b
type B struct {
	BOAIGen
}
```

and BOAIGen is defined as
```go
// BOAIGen b OAI gen
// swagger:model bOAIGen
type BOAIGen []string
```
So I am guessing the code generator is embedding the BOAIGen when it shouldn't. 
In other words, manually changing the generated code in get_all_responses.go to
```go
payload = &models.B{
	BOAIGen: make(models.BOAIGen, 0, 50),
}
```
resolves the issue and the server starts properly

Update on this one.

OAIGen types may come and go, it really depends on the $ref situation. This problem is related to the flatten vs expand problem and is more general.

On the other hand, I could work around the issue in the responses.gotmpl template (detecting type aliasing and being more careful about using `make` for arrays and maps). At least it builds, even though I don't like the introduction of these technical types.

This made me wonder about this generated construct (note I replaced `make(...)` by `&models.B1{}`:
is that double nil check below here for some purpose? This code which did not compile is after all dead code in many cases, isn't it? Please advise.

```golang
// WriteResponse to the client
func (o *GetAllOK) WriteResponse(rw http.ResponseWriter, producer runtime.Producer) {

	rw.WriteHeader(200)
	if o.Payload != nil {
		// FRED
		// .IsArray: true
		// .IsAliased: true
		// .IsMap: false
		// .IsComplexObject: true
		// .IsNullable: false
		// .IsInterface: false
		// .Zero: make(models.B1, 0, 50)
		// .IsBaseType: false
		// From above: Payload POINTER
		payload := o.Payload
		if payload == nil {
			payload = &models.B1{}
		}

		if err := producer.Produce(rw, payload); err != nil {
			panic(err) // let the recovery middleware deal with this
		}
	}
}
```
